  "prompt": "What is the proof for triangular law of vectors?",
  "response": "The triangular law of vectors states that if two vectors are represented as two sides of a triangle taken in order, then their sum is represented by the third side of the triangle taken in the reverse order. Let's break down the proof step by step.\n\nConsider two vectors \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\).\n\n1. **Draw Vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\):**\n   - Start at point \\(O\\).\n   - Draw vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) to point \\(P\\).\n\n2. **Draw Vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\):**\n   - Start at point \\(P\\).\n   - Draw vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) to point \\(Q\\).\n\nNow, to add these vectors using the triangular law:\n\n3. **Construct the Triangle:**\n   - The starting point for vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) is \\(O\\).\n   - The endpoint for vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) is \\(P\\).\n   - The starting point for vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) is \\(P\\).\n   - The endpoint for vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) is \\(Q\\).\n\n4. **Vector Addition:**\n   - According to the triangular law, the vector sum \\(\\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\\) is represented by the vector starting from \\(O\\) and ending at \\(Q\\).\n\nTo verify this geometrically, let's analyze the coordinates:\n\n- Let \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) be represented as \\( \\mathbf{A} = \\langle x_1, y_1 \\rangle \\).\n- Let \\(\\mathbf{B}\\) be represented as \\( \\mathbf{B} = \\langle x_2, y_2 \\rangle \\).\n\nIf you start at the origin \\(O(0, 0)\\) and move to point \\(P\\) by vector \\(\\mathbf{A}\\), the coordinates of \\(P\\) are \\( (x_1, y_1) \\).\n\nNow, from point \\(P (x_1, y_1)\\), you move to point \\(Q\\) by vector \\(\\mathbf{B}\\), so the coordinates of \\(Q\\) are \\( (x_1 + x_2, y_1 + y_2) \\).\n\nThe vector from \\(O\\) to \\(Q\\) represents the sum of \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) and \\(\\mathbf{B}\\):\n\n\\[\n\\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B} = \\langle x_1, y_1 \\rangle + \\langle x_2, y_2 \\rangle = \\langle x_1 + x_2, y_1 + y_2 \\rangle\n\\]\n\nHence, the vector sum \\(\\mathbf{A} + \\mathbf{B}\\) is represented by the third side of the triangle taken in the reverse order, completing the triangular law of vector addition.\n\nThis geometric interpretation provides a visual proof of the triangular law of vectors.",
